{"parse":{"title":"Raid on Hazar Qadam","pageid":35480258,"revid":832862911,"text":{"*":"<div class=\"mw-parser-output\"><p>On January 24, 2002, the American military launched an overnight raid against a \"large munitions cache\"<sup id=\"cite_ref-usembassy-israel.org.il_1-0\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-usembassy-israel.org.il-1\">&#91;1&#93;</a></sup> north of Kandahar, as part of its <a href=\"/wiki/War_in_Afghanistan_(2001%E2%80%93present)\" title=\"War in Afghanistan (2001\u2013present)\">invasion of Afghanistan</a>, claiming that it was a weapons stockpile of the <a href=\"/wiki/Taliban\" title=\"Taliban\">Taliban</a> or <a href=\"/wiki/Al-Qaeda\" title=\"Al-Qaeda\">al-Qaeda</a>. However, it was later discovered that the target was a compound that the United States had <i>asked</i> to collect weapons for the government of <a href=\"/wiki/Hamid_Karzai\" title=\"Hamid Karzai\">Hamid Karzai</a>, and that the dead and captured were all backers of the American invasion.<sup id=\"cite_ref-ReferenceA_2-0\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-ReferenceA-2\">&#91;2&#93;</a></sup><sup class=\"noprint Inline-Template\" style=\"white-space:nowrap;\">&#91;<i><a href=\"/wiki/Wikipedia:Citing_sources\" title=\"Wikipedia:Citing sources\"><span title=\"This citation requires a reference to the specific page or range of pages in which the material appears. (February 2017)\">page&#160;needed</span></a></i>&#93;</sup><sup id=\"cite_ref-3\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-3\">&#91;3&#93;</a></sup><sup id=\"cite_ref-4\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-4\">&#91;4&#93;</a></sup>\n</p>\n<div id=\"toc\" class=\"toc\"><input type=\"checkbox\" role=\"button\" id=\"toctogglecheckbox\" class=\"toctogglecheckbox\" style=\"display:none\" /><div class=\"toctitle\" lang=\"en\" dir=\"ltr\"><h2>Contents</h2><span class=\"toctogglespan\"><label class=\"toctogglelabel\" for=\"toctogglecheckbox\"></label></span></div>\n<ul>\n<li class=\"toclevel-1 tocsection-1\"><a href=\"#Battle\"><span class=\"tocnumber\">1</span> <span class=\"toctext\">Battle</span></a></li>\n<li class=\"toclevel-1 tocsection-2\"><a href=\"#Aftermath\"><span class=\"tocnumber\">2</span> <span class=\"toctext\">Aftermath</span></a></li>\n<li class=\"toclevel-1 tocsection-3\"><a href=\"#See_also\"><span class=\"tocnumber\">3</span> <span class=\"toctext\">See also</span></a></li>\n<li class=\"toclevel-1 tocsection-4\"><a href=\"#References\"><span class=\"tocnumber\">4</span> <span class=\"toctext\">References</span></a></li>\n</ul>\n</div>\n\n<h2><span class=\"mw-headline\" id=\"Battle\">Battle</span><span class=\"mw-editsection\"><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">[</span><a href=\"/w/index.php?title=Raid_on_Hazar_Qadam&amp;action=edit&amp;section=1\" title=\"Edit section: Battle\">edit</a><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">]</span></span></h2>\n<table class=\"rquote pullquote floatright\" role=\"presentation\" style=\"border-collapse:collapse; border-style:none; float:right; margin:0.5em 0.75em; width:33%;\">\n\n<tbody><tr style=\"text-align:left; vertical-align:top;\">\n<td style=\"color:#b2b7f2; font-size:3.3em; font-family:&#39;Times New Roman&#39;,serif; font-weight:bold; padding:4px 2px 2px; width:0.5em; line-height: 1em;\">\u201c\n</td>\n<td style=\"padding:0 10px;\">While we regret the loss of life, we are confident that the U.S. forces did their jobs to the best of their abilities, using the best information available to them in a very difficult situation.\n</td>\n<td style=\"color:#b2b7f2; font-size:3.3em; font-family:&#39;Times New Roman&#39;,serif; font-weight:bold; padding:4px 2px 2px; text-align:right; vertical-align:bottom; width:0.5em; line-height: 1em;\">\u201d\n</td></tr>\n<tr>\n<td class=\"rquotecite\" colspan=\"3\" style=\"padding-top:10px; font-size:smaller; line-height:normal; text-align:right;\"><cite>\u2014&#160;Department of Defense Press Release, February 21, 2002<sup id=\"cite_ref-5\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-5\">&#91;5&#93;</a></sup></cite>\n</td></tr></tbody></table>\n<p>The <a href=\"/wiki/101st_Airborne\" class=\"mw-redirect\" title=\"101st Airborne\">101st Airborne</a> was reportedly \"spoiling for a fight\", when they were given the opportunity to launch an overnight helicopter-borne assault against a school, which they characterized as \"two adjacent compounds\" in <a href=\"/w/index.php?title=Hazar_Qadam&amp;action=edit&amp;redlink=1\" class=\"new\" title=\"Hazar Qadam (page does not exist)\">Hazar Qadam</a>, 60 miles north of <a href=\"/wiki/Kandahar\" title=\"Kandahar\">Kandahar</a>.<sup id=\"cite_ref-ReferenceA_2-1\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-ReferenceA-2\">&#91;2&#93;</a></sup><sup class=\"noprint Inline-Template\" style=\"white-space:nowrap;\">&#91;<i><a href=\"/wiki/Wikipedia:Citing_sources\" title=\"Wikipedia:Citing sources\"><span title=\"This citation requires a reference to the specific page or range of pages in which the material appears. (February 2017)\">page&#160;needed</span></a></i>&#93;</sup><sup id=\"cite_ref-mich_6-0\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-mich-6\">&#91;6&#93;</a></sup><sup id=\"cite_ref-7\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-7\">&#91;7&#93;</a></sup>\n</p><p>The United States found 400 60mm mortar rounds, 300 <a href=\"/wiki/Rocket-propelled_grenade\" title=\"Rocket-propelled grenade\">RPG</a> rounds, 300 100mm rockets, thousands of fuses, 250 automatic grenade launcher rounds and more than 500,000 individual rounds for small arms,<sup id=\"cite_ref-usembassy-israel.org.il_1-1\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-usembassy-israel.org.il-1\">&#91;1&#93;</a></sup> that had been collected by their Afghan allies, and called in an <a href=\"/wiki/AC-130\" class=\"mw-redirect\" title=\"AC-130\">AC-130</a> gunship to destroy the cache.<sup id=\"cite_ref-usembassy-israel.org.il_1-2\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-usembassy-israel.org.il-1\">&#91;1&#93;</a></sup>\n</p><p>The resulting firefight at the weapons depot killed 21 Afghans, and 27 others were captured and taken to <a href=\"/wiki/Camp_Rhino\" title=\"Camp Rhino\">Camp Rhino</a> as prisoners.<sup id=\"cite_ref-ReferenceA_2-2\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-ReferenceA-2\">&#91;2&#93;</a></sup><sup class=\"noprint Inline-Template\" style=\"white-space:nowrap;\">&#91;<i><a href=\"/wiki/Wikipedia:Citing_sources\" title=\"Wikipedia:Citing sources\"><span title=\"This citation requires a reference to the specific page or range of pages in which the material appears. (February 2017)\">page&#160;needed</span></a></i>&#93;</sup> Journalist <a href=\"/wiki/Mark_Mazzetti\" title=\"Mark Mazzetti\">Mark Mazzetti</a> put the body count at over 40.<sup id=\"cite_ref-8\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-8\">&#91;8&#93;</a></sup> One American was wounded in the ankle, making him the first American military casualty since <a href=\"/wiki/Nathan_Chapman_(soldier)\" title=\"Nathan Chapman (soldier)\">Nathan Chapman</a> was the first soldier killed.<sup id=\"cite_ref-mich_6-1\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-mich-6\">&#91;6&#93;</a></sup>\n</p>\n<h2><span class=\"mw-headline\" id=\"Aftermath\">Aftermath</span><span class=\"mw-editsection\"><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">[</span><a href=\"/w/index.php?title=Raid_on_Hazar_Qadam&amp;action=edit&amp;section=2\" title=\"Edit section: Aftermath\">edit</a><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">]</span></span></h2>\n<div class=\"thumb tleft\"><div class=\"thumbinner\" style=\"width:222px;\"><a href=\"/wiki/File:Gul_Agha.jpg\" class=\"image\"><img alt=\"\" src=\"//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/0/09/Gul_Agha.jpg/220px-Gul_Agha.jpg\" width=\"220\" height=\"220\" class=\"thumbimage\" srcset=\"//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/0/09/Gul_Agha.jpg/330px-Gul_Agha.jpg 1.5x, //upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/0/09/Gul_Agha.jpg/440px-Gul_Agha.jpg 2x\" data-file-width=\"2740\" data-file-height=\"2740\" /></a>  <div class=\"thumbcaption\"><div class=\"magnify\"><a href=\"/wiki/File:Gul_Agha.jpg\" class=\"internal\" title=\"Enlarge\"></a></div>Governor <a href=\"/wiki/Gul_Agha_Sherzai\" title=\"Gul Agha Sherzai\">Gul Agha Sherzai</a> demanded information on why his officials, on the American side of the invasion, were being held as detainees.<sup id=\"cite_ref-daily_9-0\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-daily-9\">&#91;9&#93;</a></sup></div></div></div>\n<p>Early reports said that it was an al-Qaeda compound, while  General <a href=\"/wiki/Richard_Myers\" title=\"Richard Myers\">Richard Myers</a> reported that American troops had attacked a \"Taliban headquarters\", and other officials said that the captives likely included both Taliban and al-Qaeda members.<sup id=\"cite_ref-mich_6-2\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-mich-6\">&#91;6&#93;</a></sup> Over time, the US government qualified that it was likely not al-Qaeda and \"mostly of a Taliban nature\" or \"Afghan fighters\".<sup id=\"cite_ref-10\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-10\">&#91;10&#93;</a></sup> However, Afghans protested, and journalists later revealed that the depot had been collecting arms under American orders, and the captured \"fighters\" were local leaders on the Americans' side, including the district police officer.<sup id=\"cite_ref-daily_9-1\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-daily-9\">&#91;9&#93;</a></sup> The Governor of Kandahar, <a href=\"/wiki/Gul_Agha_Sherzai\" title=\"Gul Agha Sherzai\">Gul Agha Sherzai</a>, issued a statement noting that the structure had been collecting weapons as part of a weapons amnesty program organized by the United States, and that the Afghan casualties included the district police chief, his deputy and members of the district council, each of them loyal to the American-backed <a href=\"/wiki/Hamid_Karzai\" title=\"Hamid Karzai\">Hamid Karzai</a> government.<sup id=\"cite_ref-daily_9-2\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-daily-9\">&#91;9&#93;</a></sup> Eventually, the United States conceded that the attack was an instance of <a href=\"/wiki/Friendly_fire\" title=\"Friendly fire\">friendly fire</a>, and released the prisoners on February 6.<sup id=\"cite_ref-time_11-0\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-time-11\">&#91;11&#93;</a></sup> The prisoners reported that they had been beaten and abused in US custody.<sup id=\"cite_ref-time_11-1\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-time-11\">&#91;11&#93;</a></sup>\n</p><p>On February 5, Karzai noted that the attack was \"a mistake of sorts\",<sup id=\"cite_ref-12\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-12\">&#91;12&#93;</a></sup> while <a href=\"/wiki/United_States_Secretary_of_Defense\" title=\"United States Secretary of Defense\">Secretary of Defense</a> <a href=\"/wiki/Donald_Rumsfeld\" title=\"Donald Rumsfeld\">Donald Rumsfeld</a> later said that the battlefield situation had been \"untidy\" and the US had acted on \"persuasive and compelling\" intelligence.<sup id=\"cite_ref-13\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-13\">&#91;13&#93;</a></sup>\n</p><p>When it was revealed that a number of the dead had their hands tied behind their backs, the United States defended its actions, stating that it was common for troops to bind the hands of wounded enemies in a fight - and that some must have mistakenly bound the hands of already-dead Afghan villagers as well.<sup id=\"cite_ref-ReferenceA_2-3\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-ReferenceA-2\">&#91;2&#93;</a></sup><sup class=\"noprint Inline-Template\" style=\"white-space:nowrap;\">&#91;<i><a href=\"/wiki/Wikipedia:Citing_sources\" title=\"Wikipedia:Citing sources\"><span title=\"This citation requires a reference to the specific page or range of pages in which the material appears. (February 2017)\">page&#160;needed</span></a></i>&#93;</sup>\n</p>\n<div style=\"clear:both;\"></div>\n<h2><span class=\"mw-headline\" id=\"See_also\">See also</span><span class=\"mw-editsection\"><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">[</span><a href=\"/w/index.php?title=Raid_on_Hazar_Qadam&amp;action=edit&amp;section=3\" title=\"Edit section: See also\">edit</a><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">]</span></span></h2>\n<ul><li><a href=\"/wiki/2011_NATO_attack_in_Pakistan\" title=\"2011 NATO attack in Pakistan\">2011 NATO attack in Pakistan</a></li></ul>\n<h2><span class=\"mw-headline\" id=\"References\">References</span><span class=\"mw-editsection\"><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">[</span><a href=\"/w/index.php?title=Raid_on_Hazar_Qadam&amp;action=edit&amp;section=4\" title=\"Edit section: References\">edit</a><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">]</span></span></h2>\n<div class=\"reflist\" style=\"list-style-type: decimal;\">\n<div class=\"mw-references-wrap mw-references-columns\"><ol class=\"references\">\n<li id=\"cite_note-usembassy-israel.org.il-1\"><span class=\"mw-cite-backlink\">^ <a href=\"#cite_ref-usembassy-israel.org.il_1-0\"><sup><i><b>a</b></i></sup></a> <a href=\"#cite_ref-usembassy-israel.org.il_1-1\"><sup><i><b>b</b></i></sup></a> <a href=\"#cite_ref-usembassy-israel.org.il_1-2\"><sup><i><b>c</b></i></sup></a></span> <span class=\"reference-text\"><cite class=\"citation web\"><a href=\"/wiki/United_States_Department_of_Defense\" title=\"United States Department of Defense\">United States Department of Defense</a> (January 25, 2002). <a rel=\"nofollow\" class=\"external text\" href=\"https://web.archive.org/web/20020831210632/http://www.usembassy-israel.org.il/publish/peace/archives/2002/january/012606.html\">\"Taliban compound raid yielded large munitions cache\"</a>. <a href=\"/wiki/Embassy_of_the_United_States,_Tel_Aviv\" class=\"mw-redirect\" title=\"Embassy of the United States, Tel Aviv\">Embassy of the United States, Tel Aviv</a>. Archived from <a rel=\"nofollow\" class=\"external text\" href=\"http://www.usembassy-israel.org.il/publish/peace/archives/2002/january/012606.html\">the original</a> on August 31, 2002<span class=\"reference-accessdate\">. Retrieved <span class=\"nowrap\">27 February</span> 2017</span>.</cite><span title=\"ctx_ver=Z39.88-2004&amp;rft_val_fmt=info%3Aofi%2Ffmt%3Akev%3Amtx%3Abook&amp;rft.genre=unknown&amp;rft.btitle=Taliban+compound+raid+yielded+large+munitions+cache&amp;rft.pub=Embassy+of+the+United+States%2C+Tel+Aviv&amp;rft.date=2002-01-25&amp;rft.au=United+States+Department+of+Defense&amp;rft_id=http%3A%2F%2Fwww.usembassy-israel.org.il%2Fpublish%2Fpeace%2Farchives%2F2002%2Fjanuary%2F012606.html&amp;rfr_id=info%3Asid%2Fen.wikipedia.org%3ARaid+on+Hazar+Qadam\" class=\"Z3988\"><span style=\"display:none;\">&#160;</span></span></span>\n</li>\n<li id=\"cite_note-ReferenceA-2\"><span class=\"mw-cite-backlink\">^ <a href=\"#cite_ref-ReferenceA_2-0\"><sup><i><b>a</b></i></sup></a> <a href=\"#cite_ref-ReferenceA_2-1\"><sup><i><b>b</b></i></sup></a> <a href=\"#cite_ref-ReferenceA_2-2\"><sup><i><b>c</b></i></sup></a> <a href=\"#cite_ref-ReferenceA_2-3\"><sup><i><b>d</b></i></sup></a></span> <span class=\"reference-text\"><a href=\"/wiki/Stephen_Tanner\" title=\"Stephen Tanner\">Stephen Tanner</a>, \"Afghanistan: A Military History\"</span>\n</li>\n<li id=\"cite_note-3\"><span class=\"mw-cite-backlink\"><b><a href=\"#cite_ref-3\">^</a></b></span> <span class=\"reference-text\"><cite class=\"citation news\">Heintz, Jim (January 25, 2002). <a rel=\"nofollow\" class=\"external text\" href=\"http://lang.sbsun.com/socal/terrorist/0102/25/terror05.asp\">\"U.S. special forces intensify hunt, seize weapons\"</a>. <i><a href=\"/wiki/The_San_Bernardino_Sun\" title=\"The San Bernardino Sun\">The San Bernardino Sun</a></i>. <a href=\"/wiki/Associated_Press\" title=\"Associated Press\">Associated Press</a><span class=\"reference-accessdate\">. Retrieved <span class=\"nowrap\">27 February</span> 2017</span>.</cite><span title=\"ctx_ver=Z39.88-2004&amp;rft_val_fmt=info%3Aofi%2Ffmt%3Akev%3Amtx%3Ajournal&amp;rft.genre=article&amp;rft.atitle=U.S.+special+forces+intensify+hunt%2C+seize+weapons&amp;rft.date=2002-01-25&amp;rft.aulast=Heintz&amp;rft.aufirst=Jim&amp;rft_id=http%3A%2F%2Flang.sbsun.com%2Fsocal%2Fterrorist%2F0102%2F25%2Fterror05.asp&amp;rfr_id=info%3Asid%2Fen.wikipedia.org%3ARaid+on+Hazar+Qadam\" class=\"Z3988\"><span style=\"display:none;\">&#160;</span></span></span>\n</li>\n<li id=\"cite_note-4\"><span class=\"mw-cite-backlink\"><b><a href=\"#cite_ref-4\">^</a></b></span> <span class=\"reference-text\">BBC News, 24 January 2002, US troops battle Al Qa'ida militants</span>\n</li>\n<li id=\"cite_note-5\"><span class=\"mw-cite-backlink\"><b><a href=\"#cite_ref-5\">^</a></b></span> <span class=\"reference-text\"><cite class=\"citation web\"><a rel=\"nofollow\" class=\"external text\" href=\"https://web.archive.org/web/20100302001357/http://www.defense.gov/releases/release.aspx?releaseid=3245\">\"Statement on Hazar Qadam Raid\"</a>. <i>Defense.gov</i>. <a href=\"/wiki/United_States_Department_of_Defense\" title=\"United States Department of Defense\">United States Department of Defense</a>. February 21, 2002. Archived from <a rel=\"nofollow\" class=\"external text\" href=\"https://www.defense.gov/releases/release.aspx?releaseid=3245\">the original</a> on March 2, 2010<span class=\"reference-accessdate\">. Retrieved <span class=\"nowrap\">27 February</span> 2017</span>.</cite><span title=\"ctx_ver=Z39.88-2004&amp;rft_val_fmt=info%3Aofi%2Ffmt%3Akev%3Amtx%3Ajournal&amp;rft.genre=unknown&amp;rft.jtitle=Defense.gov&amp;rft.atitle=Statement+on+Hazar+Qadam+Raid&amp;rft.date=2002-02-21&amp;rft_id=https%3A%2F%2Fwww.defense.gov%2Freleases%2Frelease.aspx%3Freleaseid%3D3245&amp;rfr_id=info%3Asid%2Fen.wikipedia.org%3ARaid+on+Hazar+Qadam\" class=\"Z3988\"><span style=\"display:none;\">&#160;</span></span></span>\n</li>\n<li id=\"cite_note-mich-6\"><span class=\"mw-cite-backlink\">^ <a href=\"#cite_ref-mich_6-0\"><sup><i><b>a</b></i></sup></a> <a href=\"#cite_ref-mich_6-1\"><sup><i><b>b</b></i></sup></a> <a href=\"#cite_ref-mich_6-2\"><sup><i><b>